    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Historically, tax literature often shows that cuts to top-tier capital gains rates can increase wealth concentration because returns on existing assets accrue at a higher effective rate for the wealthy. While advocates argue for increased economic activity, critiques suggest that the immediate distributional effect favors capital owners over labor income earners. Therefore, many economic models do suggest that the statistical risk of increased inequality presents a significant counterweight to the purely investment-driven arguments. This suggests the debate balances economic theory against empirical distributional outcomes.",
      "source": "target",
